    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT150-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">iravukkuṟi nērnta tōḻikkut talaimakaḷ kūṟiyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by HER to the confidante who had granted night trysts.</p>
          </div>


        <div xml:id="KT150">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                cēṇōṉ māṭṭiya naṟumpukai ñekiḻi</l>
<l>                vāṉa mīṉiṉ vayiṉvayi ṉimaikku</l>
<l>                mōṅkumalai nāṭaṉ cāntupula rakala</l>
<l>                muḷḷi ṉuṇṇōy malkum</l>
<l>                pulliṉ māyva tevaṉko laṉṉāy.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
           <l>The chest with drying sandal paste of the man from a land</l>
           <l rend="indent4">of high mountains,</l>
           <l rend="indent">where flash forth in place after place like stars in the sky</l>
           <l rend="indent">the fire-brands with fragrant smoke,</l>
           <l rend="indent3">kindled by the [field-]guardian<note place="foot">Or rather literally: "[in turn] inflamed by one who is far"?</note>;</l>
           <l>remembering [it], [my] inner pain increases,</l>
           <l>embracing, it vanishes.</l>
           <l rend="indent2">What [is this], mother?<note place="foot">Possible would also be a construction in the sense of KT 89.3: "What (why), mother, does it vanish when embracing, | the interior pain which increases when ...".</note></l>

            </lg>
        </div>
